1. Sexual selection ≠ “what everyone should optimize for”

Sexual selection is a mechanism, not a moral directive.
	•	It explains how traits spread
	•	It does not prescribe what individuals ought to do

If everyone optimized purely for reproduction:
	•	You’d get instability (resource strain, conflict, short-term thinking)
	•	You’d lose other critical traits: builders, thinkers, stabilizers

So your instinct is right:

Not everyone should be optimizing for reproduction.

⸻

2. Evolution already solved this (quietly)

Nature doesn’t rely on everyone doing the same thing. It uses diversity of strategies.

There are always mixtures of:
	•	Reproducers → maximize propagation
	•	Investors → build resources, stability, infrastructure
	•	Explorers → take risks, generate novelty
	•	Stabilizers → maintain cohesion, norms, continuity

This isn’t philosophical—it’s how systems stay resilient.

If everyone pushes one axis, the system collapses.

⸻

3. The key mistake in your “should everyone reproduce” thought

You said:

“We don’t know whose signals should propagate”

That’s true—but evolution doesn’t require everyone to try.

It works through:
	•	variation
	•	selection
	•	filtering

If everyone maximizes reproduction:
	•	selection pressure weakens (too much noise)
	•	system quality can degrade

Paradoxically:

Constraint and selectivity improve evolution

⸻

4. Humans added a new layer: choice

Unlike animals, we can opt out of default drives.

That creates a new axis:
	•	Biological success (genes)
	•	Cultural success (ideas, systems, impact)
	•	Personal fulfillment (meaning, experience)

Someone can:
	•	Not reproduce biologically
	•	Still propagate influence massively (ideas, tech, institutions)

That’s still “selection”—just at a different layer.

⸻

5. Internal vs external optimization (what you said at the end)

This part is actually the strongest:

“Some things optimize for external growth, others for internal”

That maps cleanly:

External (expansion)
	•	reproduction
	•	exploration
	•	competition
	•	scaling systems

Internal (coherence)
	•	health
	•	relationships
	•	meaning
	•	stability

Healthy systems oscillate between the two.

Too much external:
→ burnout, collapse, exploitation

Too much internal:
→ stagnation, decay, irrelevance

⸻

6. Clean synthesis (your idea, sharpened)

Instead of:

“Everyone should optimize for reproduction”

The higher-resolution version is:

Humans operate across multiple selection layers, and a healthy system requires a diversity of strategies—some propagating genes, others propagating structure, meaning, and capability.

